<span class="displaytext"><i> excerpts from: "'values voters' flock to (candidate last)" </i> <p><i> the politico </i> </p><p><i> october 20, 2007 </i> </p><p>(candidate full) may have failed to impress beltway insiders when he finally launched his run for the white house last month, but he is winning over a critical segment of the (PARTY NAME) coalition, new polling suggests. </p><p>conservative christians favor (candidate last) by a 10-point margin over his closest rival, (candidate full). </p><p>it's a sharp reversal for (candidate last). the putative gop frontrunner had been winning social conservative backing despite his history of support for abortion rights and gay rights. </p><p>(candidate last) has changed that. </p><p>(candidate last) leads (candidate last) 29 to 21 percent among (PARTY NAME)s generally, the new national cbs news poll suggests. </p><p>but weekly (PARTY NAME) churchgoers back (candidate last) by a margin of 29 percent to 19 percent for (candidate last) -- roughly tying (candidate full). </p><p>that means that despite criticism of (candidate last) for his subdued speeches, his pregnant pauses, and his lackluster launch, the tennessean is succeeding in courting the very base of support his campaign targeted from the outset - the christian conservatives who have been the largest and most active bloc of the gop for a generation. </p><p>... </p><p>(candidate last)'s strategy seems to be working. </p><p>only a third of conservative christian (PARTY NAME)s -- defined as those who attend church at least once a week -- say they would support a candidate who disagrees with them on "social issues like abortion and same-sex marriage," according to the cbs poll taken october 12-16. </p><p>(candidate last) and (candidate last) have both disagreed with them in the past, at least as far as abortion is concerned. </p><p>... </p><p><i> to view the entire article, please visit </i> <a href="https://mail.imwithfred.com/exchweb/bin/redir.asp?url=http://www.poli